datastructures.lists

Class StaticArrayList<T>

  • java.lang.Object
    • datastructures.lists.StaticArrayList<T>
  • Type Parameters:
    T - the type held by the ArrayLinearList.
    All Implemented Interfaces:
    List<T>, java.lang.Iterable<T>

    public class StaticArrayList<T>
extends java.lang.Object
implements List<T>
    StaticArrayList is an implementation of a LinearList with an array. It does not make any practical sense, because it would be much more efficient to use a LinkedLinearList in the general case, but it is possible theoretically. The only method of the LinearList interface that is executed more efficiently in ArrayLinearList than in LinkedLinearList is the remove(int) method, which runs in O(1). Of course, other methods such as pushFront are horribly inneficient.
    Since:
    September 2013
    Author:
    Jason Filippou, jasonfil@cs.umd.edu

        public StaticArrayList(List<T> list)
        Copy constructor. Makes a deep copy of the parameter LinearList based on the elements of the current list. Note that the argument is of type LinearList, not just ArrayLinearList: we can make a copy of any kind of list to our internal representation.
        Parameters:

      • equals

        public boolean equals(java.lang.Object other)
        Standard equals() method. Two LinearLists are equal if they contain the exact same elements at the same positions. Note that this equals() method allows for comparing an ArrayLinearList with an ArrayListLinearList, and potentially allowing them to be equal because they maintain the aforementioned contract! We are interested in ADT comparison, not 1-1 memory allocation comparison.
        Overrides:
        equals in class java.lang.Object
        Parameters:
        other - The Object reference to compare to
        Returns:
        true if the two objects are considered "equal", with equality defined above.
